# IPC Architecture Patterns

## Worker/Viewer Model

- `Start-mJig` spawns a hidden background process (WMI) that performs cursor movement; the terminal becomes a viewer connected via named pipe
- Pipe name is SHA256-derived hex (no 'mJig' string)
- All pipe messages are AES-256-CBC encrypted (per-message random IV)
- Worker sends: `welcome`, `state` (every 500ms), `log`, `stopped`, `togglePause`, `focus`
- Viewer sends: `settings`, `endtime`, `output`, `title`, `viewerState`, `quit`

## Viewer Visual State Persistence

The worker maintains `$_viewerVisualState` (outputMode, previousView, windowTitle, titleEmoji, titlePresetIndex, **activeDialog**, **activeSubDialog**). Updated on every `output`, `title`, and `viewerState` message. Sent as `visualState` in every `welcome` message (plus `manualPause`).

New viewer applies it immediately after connect: restores `$Output`, `$PreviousView`, `$script:WindowTitle`, `$script:TitleEmoji`, `$script:TitlePresetIndex`, `$script:ManualPause`, and sets one of `$script:PendingReopenSettings` / `$script:_PendingReopenQuit` / `$script:_PendingReopenInfo` based on `activeDialog`, plus `$script:_PendingRestoreSubDialog`.

**`viewerState` message** (viewer → worker): `{ type='viewerState'; activeDialog=$string|$null; activeSubDialog=$string|$null }`. `activeDialog` values:
- `'settings'` — Settings panel is open (may also carry `activeSubDialog`)
- `'quit'` — Quit confirmation dialog is open (Escape or `q` key)
- `'info'` — Info/About dialog is open
- `$null` — no dialog open (sent after any dialog closes, cancels, or NeedsRedraw)

Worker uses `PSObject.Properties.Name -contains 'field'` to distinguish explicit `$null` from absent field. Settings close sync sends `output` with `activeDialog=$null`, which also clears `activeDialog` on the worker. All 4 `output` sends carry `activeDialog=$null`.

**Sub-dialog restore:** On `PendingReopenSettings` reopen, `$script:_PendingRestoreSubDialog` is consumed and passed as `-RestoreSubDialog` to `Show-SettingsDialog`. The dialog primes `$_pendingSubDialogKey` after render; first input-loop iteration consumes it. `-ViewerPipeWriter` is passed so Settings can send `viewerState` updates (`activeDialog='settings'; activeSubDialog=...`) without routing through the main loop.

**Quit/Info restore:** `$script:_PendingReopenQuit` / `$script:_PendingReopenInfo` are checked in the `$forceRedraw` block as `elseif` branches after `PendingReopenSettings`. Each: flush main frame → send `viewerState(activeDialog=...)` → call dialog → send `viewerState(activeDialog=$null)` → handle result. Quit confirmed → `break process`. Quit cancelled or NeedsRedraw → `Reset-PostDialogState` (+ inline repaint for NeedsRedraw).

**`output` message** now carries: `mode`, `epoch`, `previousView` (null if not in incognito), `settingsOpen` (always false on normal sends).

**`title` message** now carries: `windowTitle`, `titleEmoji`, `titlePresetIndex`.

## Settings Epoch Guard (Stale State Prevention)

After a viewer dialog closes, stale `state` messages in the pipe buffer could overwrite fresh values.

- Viewer increments `$_settingsEpoch` before each send, includes `epoch` in the message
- Worker captures `$_workerSettingsEpoch` from commands, includes it in `state` messages
- Viewer skips `state` messages where `$msg.epoch -lt $_settingsEpoch`
- Log and stopped messages are always processed regardless of epoch

Epoch is incremented at all 6 viewer send sites.

## Non-Blocking Writes

`Send-PipeMessageNonBlocking` uses `FlushAsync()` with a `[ref]$PendingFlush` pattern. If a previous flush is pending (viewer in dialog), the message is skipped. Critical messages (`welcome`, `stopped`, log replay) use synchronous `Send-PipeMessage`.

## Fast Disconnect Detection

Worker stores `$_viewerProcess = Get-Process -Id $_clientPid` on connect. Each 50ms tick checks `$_viewerProcess.HasExited` before any pipe I/O — detects disconnect within one tick, much faster than `IsConnected`.

## Pipe Reconnection

All `BeginWaitForConnection` calls are wrapped in try/catch. On failure, the `NamedPipeServerStream` is disposed and recreated from scratch via `New-SecurePipeServer`. All pipe instances use 64KB (65536) in/out buffer sizes.
